Introduction¶

In this project we'll be analyzing a movies dataset from Kaggle which contains basic information provided by The Movie Database (TMDb) about movies, its popularity, budget, revenue amongst others spanning from 1960 to 2015. After data preparation, the characteristics of movies are investigated in respect to the revenue, popularity, runtime and vote_average.

Dataset Description¶

This dataset contains information about 10,000 movies collected from The Movie Database (TMDb). It contains twenty-one (21) columns and below are the descriptions for each column.

Column Description:¶

id imdb_id : unique id or imdb for each movie on TMDB.
**`popularity`** : this measures how popular the movie is.

**`budget`** : the total budget of the movie in USD.

**`revenue`** : total revenue of the movie in USD.

**`original_title`** : the title of the movie.

**`cast`** : names of the cast of the movie separated by "|".

**`homepage`** : the website of the movie.

**`director`** : the name of the director(s) of the movie, it's also separated by "|" when more than 1.

**`tagline`** : a catchphrase describing the movie.

**`keywords`** : keywords related to the movie.

**`overview`** : summary of the plot of the movie.

**`runtime`** : total runtime of the movie in minutes.

**`genre`** : genres of the movie separated by "|".

**`production_companies`** : production company/companies of the movie.

**`release_date`** : release date of the movie.

**`vote_count`** : number of voters of the movie.

**`vote_average`** : average user rating of the movie.

**`release_year`** : release year of the movie ranging from 1960 to 2015.

**`budget_adj`** : the total budget of the movie in USD in terms of 2010 dollars (accounting for inlation over time).

**`revenue_adj`** : the total revenue of the movie in USD in terms of 2010 dollars (accounting for inlation over time).

Question(s) for Analysis¶

1. What genres are the most popular? What is the popularity trend by year?¶

2. Do movies with longer duration have higher rating than the short ones?¶

3. What features are associated with generating higher revenues?¶

Creating new columns and dropping the unwanted ones from the dataset¶

Some of the columns are separated by the |, so the first characters will be splitted and taken out to create a new column.
These includes the cast, director, and the genres columns.</br>

In [22]:
# Creating a function to split and extract the first character.

def split_column(x, y):
    
    df[x] = df[y].str.split(pat='|', expand = True)[0]

Creating a Bar Chart showing the Average User Rating by Duration.¶

  • The runtime will be grouped into 4 different classes depending on the quarter of percentile they belong to.

Defining a function that will:

  • Group a variable into different classes and
  • plot a bar chart of its relationship with another variable.
In [213]:
# Defining the barchart function

def barchart(x, df, names, col, label):
    
    # Setting the different classes of the variable into ranges
    min_val = df[x].min()
    low_25 = df[x].quantile(0.25)
    mid_50 = df[x].quantile(0.5)
    high_75 = df[x].quantile(0.75)
    max_val = df[x].max()

    # Setting the bin edges with classified variable 
    bin_edges = [min_val, low_25, mid_50, high_75, max_val]
   
    # Grouping the High Revenue dataframe by the different classes other variable
    df_grouped = df.groupby(pd.cut(df[x], bin_edges, labels=names))[col].mean()
    
    # Plotting the bar chart
    df_grouped.plot(kind='bar', figsize=(8,6))
    plt.xticks(rotation=0)
    plt.xlabel(label[0])
    plt.ylabel(label[1])
    plt.title(label[2])
In [211]:
# Assigning names to labels
names = ['Short', 'Not too Short', 'Long', 'Very Long']
label = ['Duration', 'Average User Rating', 'Average User Rating by the Duraation of Movies']

# Ploting the bar chart

Observation:¶

  • We can assume that duration of movies did not affect the way the users rated the movies.

We can subject this to more analysis by checking for the correlation between both variables using a scatter plot¶

In [212]:
# Defining a function to create a scatter plot

def scatter(c, df):
    
    # Increasing the size of the plot
    plt.subplots(figsize = (8,6))
    
    # Creating the scatterplot
    plt.scatter(df[c[0]], df[c[1]])
    
    # Adding the x, y labels and chart title
    plt.xlabel(c[2])
    plt.ylabel(c[3])
    plt.title(c[4])

I. Are popular movies associated with higher revenues?¶

Creating a Scatter plot showing the Correlation between Revenue & Popularity¶

  • Here, we'll create a scatter plot to check for the relationship between both variables.
In [195]:
# Scatter plot

scatter(['popularity','revenue','Popularity','Revenue','Correlation between Revenue & Popularity'], high_rev)

Observation:¶

  • There's a positive relationship between revenue and popularity.
  • It can be assumed that increase in popularity is associated with generating higher revenue.

Checking for the correlation between these variables using the correlation matrix¶

In [193]:
# Correlation matrix 

high_rev[['popularity', 'revenue']].corr()
Out[193]:
popularity revenue
popularity 1.000000 0.511167
revenue 0.511167 1.000000

Observation:¶

  • From the correlation score of 0.5, popularity of a movie is strongly correlated to its revenue.
  • There's a positive relationship between popularity and revenue.

Creating a Bar Chart showing the Revenue Generated by Popularity Class.¶

  • Here we'll create a bar chart to check the revenue generated by the different popularity class.
  • The popularity will be grouped into 4 different classes depending on the quarter of percentile they belong to.
In [197]:
# Assigning names to labels
names = ['Not Popular', 'Average', 'Popular', 'Very Popular']
label = ['Popularity Class', 'Revenue', 'Revenue Generated by Popularity Class']

# Ploting the bar chart
barchart('popularity', high_rev, names, 'revenue', label )

Observation:¶

  • As it can be seen above; the very popular movies contributed largely to the higher revenues.
  • We can also confirm that high popularity is associated with generating high revenues.

II. Does higher bugdet results in generating higher revenues?¶

Creating a Scatter plot showing the Correlation between Revenue & Budget.¶

  • Here, we'll create a scatter plot to check for the relationship between both variables.
In [196]:
# Scatter plot

scatter(['budget','revenue','Budget','Revenue','Correlation between Revenue & Budget'], high_rev)

Observation:¶

  • There's a positive relationship between revenue and budget.
  • It can be assumed that increase in popularity is associated with generating higher revenue.

Checking for the correlation between these variables using the correlation matrix¶

In [202]:
# correlation matrix

high_rev[['budget', 'revenue']].corr()
Out[202]:
budget revenue
budget 1.000000 0.556499
revenue 0.556499 1.000000

Observation:¶

  • From the correlation score of 0.6, budget of a movie is strongly correlated to its revenue.
  • There's a positive relationship between popularity and revenue.

Creating a Bar Chart showing the Revenue Generated by Budget Class¶

  • Here we'll create a bar chart to check the revenue generated by the different budget class.
  • The budget will be grouped into 4 different classes depending on the quarter of percentile they belong to.
In [201]:
# Assigning names to labels
names = ['Very Low', 'Low', 'High', 'Very High']
label = ['Budget', 'Revenue', 'Revenue Generated by Budget']

# Plotting the bar chart
barchart('budget', high_rev, names, 'revenue', label )

Observation:¶

  • As it can be seen above; the movies with very high budgets contributed largely to the higher revenues.
  • We can also confirm that high popularity is associated with generating high revenues.

Conclusions¶

  • Higher budgets and popularity were positively correlated to Higher Revenue. This is quite explainable, assuming that a higher budget for promotions and advertisements will increase the popularity of the movie. This in turn will led to generating higher revenue for the movie.
  • Also the duration of the movies, either short or very long did not affect the average user rating of the movies.
  • Over the years, there was an increase in trend for the general popularity of movies.

Limitations¶

  • At least 50% of the data for both the revenue and budget columns were dropped as they contained zeros. So this analysis was performed with a few part (only 3849 rows and 14 columns) of the original dataset.
  • Popularity and the runtime columns contained outliers as seen from the descriptive statistics.
  • The movies has multiple values for genres, casts and directors. We kept only the first names while others were dropped.
  • Hence, some of the assumptions here may not be applicable to the original dataset.
